00:30:14.500 --> 00:30:15.497
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Yes.

00:30:15.497 --> 00:30:16.190
Well, of course,
we do.

00:30:16.190 --> 00:30:18.710
If you look out in the sky,
you see stars.

00:30:18.710 --> 00:30:21.019
We see the radiation from those
stars.

00:30:21.019 --> 00:30:23.960
And so, of course,
there's radiation in all forms,

00:30:23.960 --> 00:30:27.415
heat and otherwise.
The fraction of the radiation

00:30:27.415 --> 00:30:32.259
