00:31:17.112 --> 00:31:19.717
hole and--as I remember,
the circular velocity of any

00:31:19.717 --> 00:31:21.970
object is less than the escape
velocity?

00:31:21.970 --> 00:31:22.660
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Uh-huh.

00:31:22.660 --> 00:31:24.525
Student: So couldn't you
theoretically orbit the black

00:31:24.525 --> 00:31:26.390
hole inside the event horizon
after the circular velocity?

00:31:26.390 --> 00:31:27.065
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Ah,

00:31:27.065 --> 00:31:29.523
excellent question.
Could you orbit--could you get

00:31:29.523 --> 00:31:33.220
yourself into a stable orbit
inside an event horizon?

00:31:33.220 --> 00:31:37.306
If everything were in--worked
the way Newtonian mechanics says

00:31:37.306 --> 00:31:39.723
it works, you could.
But, it turns out,

00:31:39.723 --> 00:31:41.609
there are relativistic
corrections.

00:31:41.609 --> 00:31:45.642
There is something called the
smallest circular--smallest--the

00:31:45.642 --> 00:31:51.554
Innermost Circular Stable Orbit.
IC--ISCO, Innermost Stable

00:31:51.554 --> 00:31:54.680
Circular Orbit.
That's important,

00:31:54.680 --> 00:31:57.393
because that actually can be
observed in various ways,

00:31:57.393 --> 00:31:59.849
and we'll talk about this in
two weeks' time.

00:31:59.849 --> 00:32:03.054
The Innermost Stable Circular
Orbit turns out to be outside

00:32:03.054 --> 00:32:05.098
the event horizon.
But, you're right,

00:32:05.098 --> 00:32:07.444
if you were only using
Newtonian calculations,

00:32:07.444 --> 00:32:09.529
there would be that square root
of 2,

00:32:09.529 --> 00:32:12.309
and you could imagine being in
a circular orbit inside the

00:32:12.309 --> 00:32:14.623
event horizon.
But that's one of the things

00:32:14.623 --> 00:32:17.579
that is different about the
relativistic calculation.

00:32:17.579 --> 00:32:21.563
It turns out that for
non-rotating black holes the

00:32:21.563 --> 00:32:26.685
Innermost Stable Circular Orbit
is three times the Schwarzschild

00:32:26.685 --> 00:32:28.559
radius.
Yes?

00:32:28.559 --> 00:32:35.712
Student: [Inaudible]
Professor Charles

00:32:35.712 --> 00:32:39.059
Bailyn: Ah,
yes.

00:32:39.059 --> 00:32:43.474
So, is there a potential for a
black hole to accumulate an

00:32:43.474 --> 00:32:47.423
infinite amount of mass,
