00:32:54.779 --> 00:32:57.118
Second of all,
even if there was,

00:32:57.118 --> 00:33:01.648
if there was a huge black hole
here, and something else outside

00:33:01.648 --> 00:33:06.178
the event horizon that's moving
faster than the escape velocity

00:33:06.178 --> 00:33:08.480
of this thing,
at that point,

00:33:08.480 --> 00:33:12.013
then it doesn't fall in.
So, it's not necessarily true

00:33:12.013 --> 00:33:15.450
that it will pile up an infinite
amount of mass.

00:33:15.450 --> 00:33:19.758
In fact, black holes--black
holes ought not to have infinite

00:33:19.758 --> 00:33:21.674
mass.
They ought to have a particular

00:33:21.674 --> 00:33:23.908
amount of mass.
They'll gain more as stuff

00:33:23.908 --> 00:33:27.506
falls, but if stuff doesn't fall
in, if it's moving faster than

00:33:27.506 --> 00:33:30.640
the escape velocity,
then they won't accumulate it.

00:33:30.640 --> 00:33:32.850
Student: [Inaudible]
Professor Charles

00:33:32.850 --> 00:33:35.813
Bailyn: Well it depends what
you have--we observed extremely

00:33:35.813 --> 00:33:38.055
massive holes.
It depends what you mean by

00:33:38.055 --> 00:33:40.696
"extremely massive."
The mass--most massive black

00:33:40.696 --> 00:33:43.808
holes that we know anything
about are about three billion

00:33:43.808 --> 00:33:46.588
times the mass of the Sun.
So, that's pretty massive,

00:33:46.588 --> 00:33:48.700
but it's about the same as an
ordinary galaxy.

00:33:48.700 --> 00:33:54.422
And we--what we don't have
evidence for is black holes that

00:33:54.422 --> 00:34:00.539
are substantially more massive
than whole galaxies of stars.

00:34:00.539 --> 00:34:02.309
We don't--there's no evidence
for that.

00:34:02.309 --> 00:34:04.766
So they're, basically--just to
jump ahead, they're basically

00:34:04.766 --> 00:34:07.390
two kinds of black holes that we
have empirical evidence for.

00:34:07.390 --> 00:34:11.500
One are black holes the--about
ten times the mass of the Sun.

00:34:11.500 --> 00:34:14.797
So, masses of individual stars.
Then there are the so-called

00:34:14.797 --> 00:34:17.376
supermassive black holes,
which are the masses of whole

00:34:17.376 --> 00:34:19.127
galaxies,
and those are the kinds of

00:34:19.127 --> 00:34:21.890
black holes for which we have
direct evidence at the moment.

00:34:21.890 --> 00:34:25.204
Yes?
Student: [Inaudible]

00:34:25.204 --> 00:34:28.404
Professor Charles
Bailyn: Okay,

00:34:28.404 --> 00:34:33.506
so, is it possible to detect
the presence of a black hole by

00:34:33.506 --> 00:34:37.210
looking at things around it?
Yes.

00:34:37.210 --> 00:34:40.479
That's exactly what is done,
and we'll--I'll describe this

00:34:40.479 --> 00:34:44.648
in the next couple of weeks.
But, it doesn't happen the way

00:34:44.648 --> 00:34:47.039
you suggest.
It's not like something

00:34:47.039 --> 00:34:49.757
suddenly disappears,
so we know it fell into the

00:34:49.757 --> 00:34:52.300
event horizon.
What you do is you see these

00:34:52.300 --> 00:34:55.364
things in stable orbits
around--that are perfectly happy

00:34:55.364 --> 00:34:58.150
going around in circles,
around the black hole.

00:34:58.150 --> 00:35:00.152
For example,
you can see binary stars,

00:35:00.152 --> 00:35:02.425
double stars,
in which there's a black hole

00:35:02.425 --> 00:35:05.322
and something else.
And these things are in nice

00:35:05.322 --> 00:35:07.978
stable orbits,
and you infer the properties of

00:35:07.978 --> 00:35:11.460
one object by looking at the
motion of the other object.

00:35:11.460 --> 00:35:13.320
That's exactly what we did for
the planets.

00:35:13.320 --> 00:35:16.880
And so, you can do that again
for black holes.

00:35:16.880 --> 00:35:21.146
Student: [Inaudible]
Professor Charles

00:35:21.146 --> 00:35:26.320
Bailyn: If you actually saw
something disappearing?

00:35:26.320 --> 00:35:29.789
Yeah, and in fact there
is--there is indirect evidence

00:35:29.789 --> 00:35:33.587
that there's material falling
through--that in some systems

00:35:33.587 --> 00:35:36.991
there is material currently
falling through the event

00:35:36.991 --> 00:35:39.557
horizon of black holes.
And, in fact,

00:35:39.557 --> 00:35:42.483
that's one of the things that
is a current topic of active

00:35:42.483 --> 00:35:44.639
research, is,
can you demonstrate that?

00:35:44.639 --> 00:35:47.103
If there were a black hole in
our own Solar System,

00:35:47.103 --> 00:35:48.730
anywhere near us,
we'd know it.

00:35:48.730 --> 00:35:51.699
And the reason we'd know it is,
that's a lot of mass.

00:35:51.699 --> 00:35:53.610
It would disrupt the orbits of
the planets.

00:35:53.610 --> 00:35:57.012
And as long as the planets--and
so, we have a kind of early

00:35:57.012 --> 00:35:59.788
warning system.
If a black hole cruises by,

00:35:59.788 --> 00:36:02.159
Pluto's orbit gets disturbed
first.

00:36:02.159 --> 00:36:05.745
And so, all of those nice
objects out there in the Kuiper

00:36:05.745 --> 00:36:09.714
Belt, their orbits would go all
haywire if something as massive

00:36:09.714 --> 00:36:13.107
as a stellar mass black hole
were accidentally to come

00:36:13.107 --> 00:36:15.408
nearby,
in exactly the same way they

00:36:15.408 --> 00:36:18.555
would be as if an ordinary star
of the same mass were to come

00:36:18.555 --> 00:36:20.087
by.
You wouldn't be able to see it,

00:36:20.087 --> 00:36:22.090
but the orbits of everything
would be changed rather

00:36:22.090 --> 00:36:24.409
drastically.
So, the odds of us actually

00:36:24.409 --> 00:36:27.291
falling into a black hole are
extremely small,

00:36:27.291 --> 00:36:30.429
and if it were to happen,
we'd get a great deal of

00:36:30.429 --> 00:36:33.800
advance notice.
So, not to worry.

00:36:33.800 --> 00:36:38.238
There are astronomical things
you maybe should worry about,

00:36:38.238 --> 00:36:42.829
asteroids crashing into the
